INSERT INTO `widok_evo_site_tmplvar_contentvalues` VALUES ('1708','79','366','{\"fieldValue\":[{\"url\":\"<a href=\\\"https://lodz.academia.edu/TomaszZa%C5%82uski\\\" target=\\\"_blank\\\">academia.edu</a>\"}],\"fieldSettings\":{\"autoincrement\":1}}');
INSERT INTO `widok_evo_site_tmplvar_contentvalues` VALUES ('1709','80','366','{\"fieldValue\":[{\"title\":\"Instytut Kultury Współczesnej, Uniwersytet Łódzki\",\"url\":\"http://www.kulturoznawstwo.uni.lodz.pl/pracownicy/26-pracownicy/pracownicy-katedry-mediow-i-kultury-audiowizualnej/1216-dr-tomasz-zauski\"}],\"fieldSettings\":{\"autoincrement\":1}}');
INSERT INTO `widok_evo_site_tmplvar_contentvalues` VALUES ('1710','37','332','<p>The avant-garde has been often considered as an attempt to integrate art with the praxis of everyday life and as an enterprise of designing the social change and creating visions of the new man, new culture and new society. This has led to interpreting the avant-garde as a radical but also &ndash; utopian artistic and cultural movement. Less often, even nowadays, the avant-garde is described and defined in terms of necessity and capability of creating new circumstances for radical artistic and socio-political ideas to get culturally enrooted, socially legitimised, and politically implemented. In order to create these appropriate circumstances, the avant-garde had to be able to function and perform efficiently within the real conditions of a particular time and place. It is here that the so-called &ldquo;utopism&rdquo; of the avant-garde got replaced by or at least supplemented with its operativity, good judgement and effectivity, enterprising spirit and resourcefulness &ndash; that is with its ability, sometimes highly developed, to self-organise and self-institutionalise in the public sphere.</p>\n<p>The article focuses on artistic and organisational practices of Polish constructivist artist Władysław Strzemiński, especially on his expanded idea of art as an agent of cultural and social modernisation. The author shows how in Strzemiński\'s case the modernisation imperative translated into what can be called a &ldquo;double politics&rdquo;. Strzemiński\'s successful attempt at creating the International Collection of Modern Art, which later became the basis of the Muzeum Sztuki in Ł&oacute;dź as a museum of the avant-garde, is briefly situated in this context. The point is to show what role the collection, deposited in a municipal museum in Ł&oacute;dź and made accessible to the general public, was to play in the artist\'s overall modernisation politics. In the second part of the article, the author reflects on the possibility of repurposing and updating the idea of the &ldquo;Museum of Artistic Culture&rdquo; as an institution capable of providing a relevant and responsible answer to the avant-garde\'s ethos and heritage of modernisation. It is done with reference to the project entitled&nbsp;<em>The Effectivity of Art</em>, organised by himself on the invitation from the Muzeum Sztuki in the years 2012-2014. It is one of the projects through which the institution has been trying to work with and re-work this modernisation heritage of the avant-garde in the sphere of contemporary artistic and activist practices.</p>');
INSERT INTO `widok_evo_site_tmplvar_contentvalues` VALUES ('1711','81','332','<p></p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote1anc\" name=\"sdfootnote1sym\">1</a>The text is a&nbsp;modified version of a&nbsp;paper delivered at the conference <em>Museum of the Avant-garde or the Avant-garde Museum? Collecting the Radical</em>, organized by the Muzeum Sztuki in Ł&oacute;dź, Poland, 2-3.12.2017.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote2anc\" name=\"sdfootnote2sym\">2</a>The following abbreviations have been used in the article for the collected texts and letters of Władysław Strzemiński that are repeatedly cited: W&nbsp;&ndash; Władysław Strzemiński, <em>Pisma</em> [Collected Writings], (Wrocław: Zakład Narodowy im. Ossolińskich &ndash; Wydawnictwo, 1975); L &ndash; &ldquo;Listy Władysława Strzemińskiego do Juliana Przybosia z&nbsp;lat 1929-1933&rdquo; [The Letters of Władysław Strzemiński to Julian Przyboś, 1929-1993], ed. Andrzej Turowski, <em>Rocznik Historii Sztuki</em>, 1973, vol. 9.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote3anc\" name=\"sdfootnote3sym\">3</a>Karl Marx, <em>The Eighteenth Brumaire of Louis Bonaparte</em>, (Moscow: Progress Publishers, 1972), 10.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote4anc\" name=\"sdfootnote4sym\">4</a>Yve-Alain Bois, &ldquo;Strzemiński and Kobro: In search of motivation,&rdquo; in: idem, <em>Painting as Model</em> (Cambridge: MIT Press, 1993) 135.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote5anc\" name=\"sdfootnote5sym\">5</a>Andrzej Turowski, <em>Konstruktywizm polski</em> [Polish Constructivism], (Wrocław: Zakład Narodowy im. Ossolińskich &ndash; Wydawnictwo, 1981), 225-226. While admitting that Strzemiński was critical of the actual destructive impact of communism on art, Turowski nevertheless suggests that the artist seemed to have a&nbsp;more positive approach to communism as long as it formed &ldquo;the social air and atmosphere&rdquo; and was understood as a&nbsp;&ldquo;standpoint on the phenomena of individual and social life&rdquo; and a&nbsp;&ldquo;general life attitude&rdquo;, rather than simply as &ldquo;a political or propaganda tendency&rdquo; &ndash; ibid. However, in the late 1990s Turowski changes his analytical perspective and situates both Katarzyna Kobro and Władysław Strzemiński in the context of social solidarism and cooperativism, see &ndash; idem, <em>Awangardowe marginesy</em> [The Margins of the Avant-Garde] (Warszawa: Instytut Kultury, 1998), 127.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote6anc\" name=\"sdfootnote6sym\">6</a>Stanisław Czekalski, <em>Harmonia totalna. Tayloryzm i&nbsp;unizm</em> [A Total Harmony. Taylorism and Unism], an unpublished paper delivered at the <em>Katarzyna Kobro 1898-1851. W&nbsp;stulecie urodzin</em> conference [Katarzyna Kobro 1898-1851. On the centenary of her birth], organized by the Muzeum Sztuki in Ł&oacute;dź, Poland, 23.10.1998.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote7anc\" name=\"sdfootnote7sym\">7</a>Kazimierz Piotrowski, &ldquo;Strzemiński i&nbsp;Chwistek &ndash; sp&oacute;r o&nbsp;esencjalizm w&nbsp;kontekście krytyki pseudomodernizmu&rdquo; [Strzemiński and Chwistek &ndash; a&nbsp;Dispute on Essentialism in the Context of Critiques of Pseudo-Modernism] in: <em>Władsław Strzemiński. </em><em>Uniwersalne oddziaływanie idei</em> [Władysław Strzemiński. The Universal Impact of Ideas], ed. G. Sztabiński (Ł&oacute;dź: Akademia Sztuk Pięknych im. Władysława Strzemińskiego, 2005), 39.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote8anc\" name=\"sdfootnote8sym\">8</a>Iwona Luba, &ldquo;Paradoks sztuki oficjalnej. Polsko-rosyjsko-radziecki galimatias&rdquo; [The Official Art Paradox. A&nbsp;Polish-Russian-Soviet Hotchpotch] in: <em>Polska &ndash; Rosja. </em><em>Sztuka i&nbsp;historia / Poland &ndash; Russia. Art and History</em>, Vol. II, eds. Jerzy Malinowski, Irina Gavrash, Zofia Krasnopolska-Wesner (Warszawa-Toruń: Polski Instytut Studi&oacute;w nad Sztuką Świata &amp; Wydawnictwo Tako, 2014), 239.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote9anc\" name=\"sdfootnote9sym\">9</a>Aandrzej Turowski, <em>Malewicz w&nbsp;Warszawie</em> [Malevich in Warsaw], (Krak&oacute;w: Universitas, 2004), 74.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote10anc\" name=\"sdfootnote10sym\">10</a>Marian Minich, &ldquo;Szalona galeria&rdquo; [A Crazy Gallery], in: A. Minich-Scholz, <em>Marian Minich &ndash; pod wiatr</em>; M. Minich, <em>Wspomnienia wojenne. </em><em>Szalona galeria</em> (Warszawa: Książka i&nbsp;Prasa, 2015), 231-232.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote11anc\" name=\"sdfootnote11sym\">11</a>There is a&nbsp;growing body of literature which uses the modernization perspective to analyze the Polish avant-garde in its complex relationships with other artistic, cultural and social phenomena of the interwar and postwar period, see Andrzej Szczerski, <em>Modernizacje. </em><em>Sztuka i&nbsp;architektura w&nbsp;nowych państwach Europy Środkowo-Wschodniej 1918-1939 </em>[Modernizations. Art and Architecture in the New Countries of Central and Eastern Europe 1918-1939]<em>, </em>(Ł&oacute;dź: Muzeum Sztuki w&nbsp;Łodzi, 2011); Iwona Luba, <em>Duch romantyzmu i&nbsp;modernizacja. Sztuka oficjalna Drugiej Rzeczypospolitej</em> [The Spirit of Romanticism and Modernization. The Official Art of the Second Polish Republic], (Warszawa: Neriton, 2012); <em>Socrealizmy i&nbsp;modernizacje</em> [Social Realisms and Modernisations], eds. Aleksandra Sumorok, omasz Załuski (Ł&oacute;dź: Akademia Sztuk Pięknych im. W. Strzemińskiego w&nbsp;Łodzi, 2017); <em>Szklane domy. Wizje i&nbsp;praktyki modernizacji społecznych po roku 1918</em> [Glass Houses. The Visions and Practices of Social Modernisations after 1918], ed. Joanna Kordjak (Warszawa: Zachęta &ndash; Narodowa Galeria Sztuki, 2018). The modernization perspective has also been applied to Strzemiński, and more precisely, to his ideas and practices after 1945 &ndash; see Andrzej Szczerski, &ldquo;Strzemiński &ndash; the Moderniser,&rdquo; in: <em>Powidoki życia. </em><em>Władysław Strzemiński i&nbsp;prawa dla sztuki / Afterimages of life. Władysław Strzemiński and Rights for Art</em>, ed. Jarosław Lubiak (Ł&oacute;dź: Muzeum Sztuki w&nbsp;Łodzi, 2012), 225&ndash;245.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote12anc\" name=\"sdfootnote12sym\">12</a>I developed my argument on Strzemiński&rsquo;s &bdquo;double politics&rdquo; elsewhere &ndash; see Tomasz Załuski, &ldquo;Władysław Strzemiński po wojnie: modernizacja, marksizm, socrealizm&rdquo; [Władysław Strzemiński after World War II: modernisation, Marxism, Social Realism], in: <em>Socrealizmy i&nbsp;modernizacje</em>, 229-237.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote13anc\" name=\"sdfootnote13sym\">13</a>Katarzyna Kobro, Władysław Strzemiński, &ldquo;Kto chce, niech szpera... Manifest grupy a.r.&rdquo; [Forage Around, Those Who Want It... A&nbsp;Manifesto of the a.r. group], in: <em>Strzemiński &ndash; In Memoriam</em>, ed. Janusz Zagrodzki, (Ł&oacute;dź: Sztuka Polska, 1988), 183.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote14anc\" name=\"sdfootnote14sym\">14</a>For an expanded presentation and analysis of Kobro and Strzemiński&rsquo;s Taylorist biopolitics see T. Załuski, &ldquo;Futerał na ciało. Tayloryzm i&nbsp;biopolityka w&nbsp;koncepcji architektury funkcjonalistycznej Katarzyny Kobro i&nbsp;Władysława Strzemińskiego&rdquo; [A Case for the Body. Taylorism and Biopolitics in Katarzyna Kobro and Władysław Strzemiński&rsquo;s Concept of Functionalist Architecture], in: <em>Architektura przymusu</em> [The Architecture of Coercion], eds. M. Domański, T. Ferenc (Ł&oacute;dź: Akademia Sztuk Pięknych im. W. Strzemińskiego w&nbsp;Łodzi, 2013), 21-37. See also Jarosław Suchan, Kobro &amp; Strzemiński. &ldquo;Prototypes of a&nbsp;new thinking,&rdquo; in: <em>Kobro &amp; Strzemiński. Avant-garde Prototypes</em>, exhib. cat. (Madrid: Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sofia, 2017), 17-67.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote15anc\" name=\"sdfootnote15sym\">15</a>See for example W, 157, 217 and Katarzyna Kobro, <em>Funkcjonalizm</em> [Functionalism], in: Nika Strzemińska, <em>Katarzyna Kobro</em>, (Warszawa: Wydawnictwo Naukowe Scholar, 2004), 79-80.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote16anc\" name=\"sdfootnote16sym\">16</a>On this subject see Agata Zysiak, <em>Punkty za pochodzenie. Powojenna modernizacja i&nbsp;uniwersytet w&nbsp;robotniczym mieście</em>, [Affirmative Action. Postwar Modernization and University in the Working Class City], (Krak&oacute;w: Nomos, 2016).</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote17anc\" name=\"sdfootnote17sym\">17</a>Andrzej Turowski, <em>Muzea Kultury Artystycznej</em> [Museums of Artistic Culture], <em>Artium Quaestiones</em> 1983, no. 2, 89-103. Also available in English translation as &ldquo;&lsquo;The Contemporary Museum is a&nbsp;Laboratory of Knowledge&rsquo;: The Origins of the Museum of Contemporary Art in Russia&rdquo;, in: <em>From Museum Critique to the Critical Museum</em>, eds. Katarzyna Murawska-Muthesius, Piotr Piotrowski, (London: Routledge, 2015).</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote18anc\" name=\"sdfootnote18sym\">18</a>For more information on the Petrograd Conference and the issue of Museums of Artistic Culture in post-revolutionary Russia see Maria Gough, <em>Futurist Museology</em>, <em>Modernism / Modernity</em> 2003, vol. 10, no. 2, 327-348. See also the relevant source texts gathered in: <em>Avant-Garde Museology</em>, ed. Arseny Zhilyaev, (Minneapolis: e-flux, V-A-C Foundation and University of Minnesota Press, 2015), 282-306.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote19anc\" name=\"sdfootnote19sym\">19</a><em>Skuteczność sztuki</em> [The Effectiveness of Art], ed. Tomasz Załuski, (Ł&oacute;dź: Muzeum Sztuki in Ł&oacute;dź, 2014).</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote20anc\" name=\"sdfootnote20sym\">20</a>This classic motif of the politicization of art appears as one of the ways of making art socially effective in Artur Żmijewski\'s &ldquo;manifesto&rdquo; &ndash; see A. Żmijewski, &ldquo;The applied social arts&rdquo;, on-line, <a href=\"http://www.artmargins.com/index.php/featured-articles/119-the-applied-social-arts-\">http://www.artmargins.com/index.php/featured-articles/119-the-applied-social-arts-</a>, accesseed 18 September 2018.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote21anc\" name=\"sdfootnote21sym\">21</a>A contemporary version of this avant-garde motif can be found for example in Nicolas Bourriaud, <em>Relational Aesthetics</em>, trans. Simon Pleasance and Fronza Woods (Paris: Les presses du r&eacute;el, 2002).</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote22anc\" name=\"sdfootnote22sym\">22</a>This seems to be Grant Kester\'s position &ndash; see for example his <em>Conversation Pieces: Community and Communication in Modern Art</em> (Berkeley: University of California Press, 2004) and <em>The One and the Many: Contemporary Collaborative Art in a&nbsp;Global Context</em> (Durham: Duke University Press, 2011).</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote23anc\" name=\"sdfootnote23sym\">23</a>See for example Claire Bishop, &ldquo;The Social Turn: Collaboration and its Discontents&rdquo;, in: <em>Artforum</em> 44, 2006, no. 6, 178-183.</p>\n<p><a href=\"#sdfootnote24anc\" name=\"sdfootnote24sym\">24</a>For the Polish context, see for example Rafał Jakubowicz, <em>O praktykach artwashingu oraz kulturze i&nbsp;sztuce jako narzędziu penalizacji biedy i&nbsp;gentryfikacji</em> [On Artwashing Practices, Culture and Art as Tools of Gentrification and the Penalisation of Poverty], on-line, <a href=\"http://www.nowakrytyka.pl/pl/artykuly/Nk_on-line/?id=969/O_praktykach_artwashingu\">http://www.nowakrytyka.pl/pl/artykuly/Nk_on-line/?id=969/O_praktykach_artwashingu</a>, accessed 18 September 2018.</p>');
